const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Are peptides safe for men?",
    answer:
      "It depends entirely on which one. FDA-approved peptide drugs have known safety profiles from trials that included men. Research chemicals have no established human safety profile, no verified purity, and no long-term data. The word “peptide” carries no safety information on its own.",
  },
  {
    question: "Is BPC-157 legal in 2026?",
    answer:
      "It came off FDA Category 2 in April 2026, which removed a prohibition designation but did not authorize compounding. It went before the advisory committee on July 23, 2026, with FDA staff recommending against inclusion. Any legal pathway would still require FDA acceptance plus rulemaking. Check the current status before relying on any claim.",
  },
  {
    question: "Do peptides increase testosterone?",
    answer:
      "Growth hormone secretagogues do not directly raise testosterone. hCG and enclomiphene work on the HPG axis and can. Weight loss on GLP-1 medications frequently raises testosterone in men with obesity-related hypogonadism.",
  },
  {
    question: "Will peptides affect my fertility?",
    answer:
      "GH secretagogues generally do not. Testosterone does, substantially — azoospermia occurs in roughly 65% of men on TRT. hCG co-administration is the established approach to preserving spermatogenesis, and it works better started early than started late.",
  },
  {
    question: "Does MK-677 build muscle?",
    answer:
      "It raises GH and IGF-1 and increases appetite and body weight, with much of the early gain being water. It also impairs insulin sensitivity and carries a cardiac safety signal that ended its clinical development. It is banned in tested sport and by the DoD.",
  },
  {
    question: "Will BPC-157 heal my tendon injury?",
    answer:
      "No human randomized trial has tested that. The claim rests on rodent data. Loading protocols supervised by a physiotherapist have actual evidence behind them for tendinopathy.",
  },
];

